doc.str: Joanna Anderson covers legislation on legal affairs, immigration, homeland security and foreign policy issues as a staff writer for Congressional Quarterly. She first joined CQ as an assistant editor for its government documents product and previously completed several Senate internships, including with a leadership office and the Foreign Relations Committee on Capitol Hill and as a press intern in a senator's state office. Originally from suburban Philadelphia, Joanna is a graduate of George Washington University, where she earned a degree in political science. She currently lives in the Upper Northwest area of the District.

Bill Clark has been a staff photographer with Roll Call since 2006 and has been covering Washington since 2000. His career in photojournalism began in 1987 as a photo researcher for US News & World Report soon after graduating from the University of Maryland with a degree in Government and Politics. Bill has received numerous awards for his photography from the Virginia News Photographers Association, National Press Photographers Association, White House News Photographers Association and Pictures of the Year International.

Rebecca Adams has covered all of the major legislative health care battles since 1998, including the 2003 Medicare prescription drug bill and the 2010 health care overhaul. She temporarily changed beats to cover the Bush administration's policies on energy and the environment. She also served as a general domestic policy regulatory reporter for CQ Weekly magazine for a couple of years. She has freelanced for many publications, including The Washington Post and USA Today. Before coming to Washington in early 1998, Adams wrote for The Arizona Republic, The Chattanooga Times and The Macon Telegraph. She was a stringer for The New York Times in Tennessee. She graduated from Emory University with a B.A. in political science.

Mike Christensen has been an editor at CQ Roll Call since 1996 for CQ Weekly and now, the Member Information team for CQ.com. Before joining CQ, he was a reporter for the Atlanta Journal and Constitution for 24 years, the last seven in Washington, and he covered the 1984 and 1988 presidential campaigns.

Randy Leonard has expanded CQ Roll Call's data visualization expertise with interactive maps and graphics. He is also a data reporter and previously covered energy policy. Before joining CQ Roll Call in 2013, he worked as a freelance reporter for The New York Times, covering issues including police misconduct allegations and political corruption. He worked previously for a community paper outside of Baltimore and has a background as an environmental scientist conducting investigations at fuel sites.
Mark Stricherz is a capital-markets reporter and analyst for CQ Legal. He covers IPO’s as well as crowdfunding legislation related to the Jobs Act of 2012.

Tom Williams has been a staff photographer for Roll Call since 2000 where he started as a photo intern. He has covered numerous national party conventions, races for House and Senate seats, and the Gulf Coast oil spill. He started taking pictures at 16 years old and his grandfather was one of his primary subjects. Today, friends and family remain an inspiration for his photographs. He is from Tunkhannock, Pa., and holds to two B.A. degrees from Penn State University. His favorite photographer is Henri Cartier-Bresson and favorite musician is Bob Dylan.

Paul Jenks provides readers each weekday morning a clear and concise update and narrative of legislative and regulatory developments on health care topics. Jenks has also joined the CQ Now team, in addition to his work on HealthBeat.
Jenks is a veteran observer of legislative process, particularly the documents that drive the debate on contentious topics. He has overseen the development of methods of clearly tracking Congressional and regulatory actions starting with the pioneer Legi-Slate service and has adapted new reporting for GalleryWatch, Roll Call and CQ.

Catalina Camia manages the Money and Influence coverage of CQ.com and reporters who specialize in political money, lobbying, immigration and data-driven journalism. She has extensive experience in politics and elections as an editor and reporter. Prior to joining CQ Roll Call, Camia was a national political correspondent for USA TODAY and the anchor of the OnPolitics blog. At USA TODAY, Camia was co-director of 2008 presidential campaign coverage and an assignment editor focused on the 2006 and 2010 congressional elections. She has also been an editor overseeing coverage of campaign finance, economics, the White House and NASA. Camia previously covered Congress for The Dallas Morning News and got her start in Washington as an environmental policy reporter for CQ. She is a former national president of the Asian American Journalists Association and UNITY: Journalists of Color. Camia is a graduate of the University of Southern California.

Bridget Bowman keeps her eye what's happening on and around the Hill. She covers the Senate, local elections, the Capitol Hill community, House and Senate administration, legislative agencies and congressional oversight over the District of Columbia. Bowman joined Roll Call from PBS NewsHour, where she was a broadcast desk assistant on the politics team and participated in the production of the daily program. She graduated with a political science degree from the College of the Holy Cross, where she wrote for the campus newspaper and interned at Meet the Press as part of the Washington Semester Program. Bowman is from Buffalo, N.Y.

Meredith Dake-O'Connor moved to join the CQ Roll Call team as the multimedia editor in Washington, D.C., from her home in Oklahoma City in December of 2013. Outside of her specialty in breaking news video and editorial content, Meredith has a background in HR/training and development as well as energy-related legal research. She currently lives in Maryland.

JM Rieger oversees video production for Roll Call. He began his career as an editorial intern for Roll Call in 2013 and started full time as Roll Call's video editor in September 2013. Prior to joining Roll Call, he interned at Fox Sports in Los Angeles, NBC's "Meet the Press" and Performics, a Chicago-based performance-marketing company. JM graduated with honors from Miami University with degrees in journalism and political science. At Miami he worked as an editor for The Miami Student, covering higher education, campus life and sports, and also worked as a broadcaster and producer for the campus television and radio stations.
Cameron Easley is Roll Call's managing editor.

Stephen Gettinger has covered Congress as a reporter and editor for CQ since 1984, spending short stints at Bloomberg News and National Journal. He is deputy editor of CQ Weekly. He specializes in congressional history, leadership, the federal budget and CQ's hallmark vote studies. He is also the author of a book on capital punishment and was a finalist for a National Magazine Award.

Anne L. Kim is a legislative action reporter for CQ Roll Call. She covers committee markups and House and Senate floor action on science, technology and transportation legislation. Anne started at CQ as an editorial assistant. Her past reporting experiences include internships at The Associated Press in Seattle, The Seattle Times and the Richmond Times-Dispatch. She has also has written stories for the International Examiner newspaper in Seattle. Anne graduated from University of Washington, where she majored in International Studies and English. She lives in DC's Cleveland Park neighborhood.

Alex Clearfield is a researcher for the Members team at CQ, which tracks Members of Congress and congressional elections. He joined CQ in April 2015 as a researcher for the advocacy and engagement team. Prior to CQ he interned on Capitol Hill, with two nonprofit advocacy groups, and with a political consulting firm. He is a South Jersey native, Johns Hopkins graduate, and current resident of Silver Spring, Md.

Nathan L. Gonzales is Editor & Publisher of The Rothenberg & Gonzales Political Report, a non-partisan newsletter covering U.S. House, Senate and gubernatorial campaigns and Presidential politics. He was an editor, analyst, and writer for The Rothenberg Political Report for more than 13 years before taking over the newsletter in 2015. Nathan is also Founder and Publisher of PoliticsinStereo.com, which features state-based political news from the Left, the Right and non-partisan sources. Since 2002, Nathan has worked as an off-air consultant for ABC NEWS on their Election Night Decision Desk. Previously, he worked for CNN.com and as associate producer for CNN's Capital Gang. Nathan has appeared on NBC's Meet the Press and NBC Nightly News, the Newshour on PBS, C-SPAN's Washington Journal, CNN, and Fox News Channel, and he has been quoted in The New York Times, Washington Post, Wall Street Journal, and USA Today. His work has also appeared on FiveThirtyEight, WashingtonPost.com, NBCLatino.com and in Campaigns & Elections magazine. Nathan grew up in Oregon, earned his M.A. from the George Washington University's Graduate School of Political Management (Washington, DC) and his B.A. from Vanguard University (Costa Mesa, California). He first came to Washington, D.C. as an intern in the White House Press Office and now lives in the city with his wife and three children.

Sean McMinn is a data journalist at CQ Roll Call. He analyzes databases and finds the stories behind them, mostly at federal and national levels. He publishes to both CQ and Roll Call as a writer, graphic designer and interactive developer. McMinn previously covered federal politics and policy at USA Today, the Scripps Washington bureau and the San Luis Obispo Tribune.

Tom Curry covers the transportation community in Washington for CQ.com. He has been a national affairs reporter and editor for nearly two decades, having covered elections, Supreme Court nominations, fiscal policy and the health care debate.

John T. Bennett is the White House correspondent for Roll Call. Before joining CQ Roll Call, Bennett was the senior congressional reporter for Defense News. He has covered the "fiscal cliff" crisis, the Ryan-Murray budget deal, and high-level talks about a sweeping fiscal deal. He covered national security issues for over a decade previously and earned a master's degree from Johns Hopkins University in Global Security Studies.

Ellyn Ferguson reports on agriculture and food issues for CQ Roll Call. For nearly 20 years she worked as a Washington-based reporter for Gannett covering the overhaul of federal welfare programs and the writing of several farm policy bills, including the 1996 overhaul. She is a member of the North American Agricultural Journalists and the National Press Club and is former president of the Regional Reporters Association. Ellyn graduated from the University of Florida in Gainesville with a degree in journalism.

Ed is a native of southern Illinois, where his mom and sister live in the historic Ohio River community of Shawneetown. He got his undergraduate degree at Trinity University in San Antonio and began his career in news as a researcher in the former Knight-Ridder Washington bureau. Ed returned to Illinois to earn his postgraduate degree from the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University. Following a second stint at the Knight-Ridder bureau as an intern, he wrote for local newspapers in Pasadena, Calif. and Rochester, Minn. From there, Ed returned to Washington during the administration of George H.W. Bush. He was a writer and bureau chief for the Small Newspaper Group chain of Midwest dailies through 2008. Ed then moved to The Washington Times in 2009 as an energy reporter and has been the lead reporter with the independent spinoff Energy Guardian since 2010. Ed and his wife Mary live in Southwest Washington and spend their free time taking in the views of the Shenandoah Valley and the Rockies on their tandem touring bike.

Jennifer Koons oversees CQ.com's defense coverage, including the Pentagon, foreign policy and homeland security. She has a background in national security law and foreign policy issues, including continued fallout on the Arab Spring and the rise of ISIS. In May 2014 she returned from Niger, where, as a recipient of a Pulitzer Center for Crisis Reporting grant, she investigated the root causes that have allowed Boko Haram and like-minded extremist groups to thrive in the region. Her work has appeared in The New York Times, Washington Post, Foreign Policy, GlobalPost, Salon and Huffington Post. Koons previously lived in Doha, Qatar.

Niels Lesniewski covers the Senate for Roll Call. He joined what is now CQ Roll Call in September 2007, hired by Roll Call for the GalleryWatch legislative tracking service that was integrated into CQ in 2009. He is known for his expertise on the peculiarities of Senate procedure. Niels began covering the Senate for CQ.com in January 2010, taking the title of CQ SenateWatch editor in the summer of 2011. He has contributed to coverage of all the biggest policy stories on Capitol Hill in recent years, including the response to the 2008 financial collapse, the health care overhaul and several budget standoffs. A Connecticut native, Niels graduated from Hamilton College in New York with a dual degree in theatre and government. Before joining CQ Roll Call, he worked for theater productions in D.C. and New England. While in college, he interned for ABC's "This Week with George Stephanopoulos." Outside of work, Niels is an avid sports fan. He started attending Nationals games back when the team was among the worst in the National League and still playing at RFK Stadium.

Patricia Murphy covers national politics for the Daily Beast. Previously, she was the Capitol Hill Bureau Chief for Politics Daily, founder and editor of Citizen Jane Politics, and a contributor to The Washington Post's She the People blog. Before working in journalism, Patricia was a staffer for three senators. She graduated from Vanderbilt University and holds a master's degree in journalism from Columbia University.

Jason Dick Roll Call's senior writer. He was previously the publication's Capitol Hill editor, Heard on the Hill editor and House leadership editor. Prior to his time at Roll Call, he was editor of National Journal Daily and its predecessor publication, CongressDaily. He began his journalism career in Washington at National Journal's environmental news daily, GreenWire, in 1998. A native of Arizona and a resident of Capitol Hill, he has also worked for the AmeriCorps program in West Virginia, and taught in Arizona and West Virginia.
David is a Legislative Action Intern for CQ Roll Call.

Ryan Kelly is a politics, government and media-obsessed data editor for CQ Roll Call. He joined CQ’s magazine research and data team in 2006, after serving four years as a non-partisan economic development aide for a Central California congressional office. In his spare time, Ryan is a photographer and geeks out over film, Bay Area sports, indie rock music, food, comic books and technology.

doc.str: Steve is the vice president and news director for CQ.

Gillian Roberts in an editor for CQ Now. A native of Chicago, Gillian is a graduate of Northwestern University's Medill School of Journalism, and toiled as a weekend White House freelancer for Bloomberg.

Gnoffo oversees CQ's State Report as well as coverage of federal energy, environment, education and labor policy. Before joining CQ he helped direct Bloomberg News' coverage of U.S. financial regulation in Washington. Previously, he was an award-winning reporter and business editor during a 22-year career at The Philadelphia Inquirer, and later served as managing editor of Knowledge@Wharton, the online business journal of the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School. He is a graduate of Rutgers University and lives in Takoma Park, Md.

Sarah Chacko started as a legislative action reporter for CQ Roll Call in November 2012. Prior to that, she covered government contract and grant spending for the Federal Times and the Louisiana state legislature for The Advocate in Baton Rouge. Sarah also worked in Texas as an education reporter for the Denton Record-Chronicle and city hall reporter for the Killeen Daily Herald. Sarah is a 2004 graduate of Texas Christian University and a 2011 graduate of Northwestern University's Medill School of Journalism.

Roll Call editor-in-chief Melinda Henneberger has worked for Bloomberg Politics, the Washington Post, the Dallas Morning News and for 10 years the New York Times, where she was a Washington correspondent and Rome bureau chief. She was also founding editor of AOL's Politics Daily and a fellow at the Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Public of Harvard's Kennedy School.

Simone Pathé covers congressional campaigns at Roll Call. She joined the team in April 2015. She previously covered economics as a reporter/producer for the PBS NewsHour and editor of correspondent Paul Solman's popular Making Sen$e blog. She's written about everything from Bitcoin gambling and monetary policy to Janet Yellen's selfies, and she established a partnership between the NewsHour and the National Bureau of Economic Research in 2014 to explain academic research to a wider audience. Pathé graduated from Bates College in 2011 with degrees in comparative politics and French. She studied abroad in Paris and Rwanda and loves all things Francophone. A New Jersey native, Pathé resides in the District of Columbia.

Jeremy Dillon covers congressional energy and environment policy for CQ.com. Originally from Easton, Pa., Dillon graduated from Villanova University in 2013 with a degree in communications and specialization in journalism. He previously worked for ExchangeMonitor Publications, covering the radioactive waste industry as well as the federal government's cleanup of legacy Cold-War nuclear sites. In his free time, he enjoys watching basketball and eating pizza.

John Helton is Roll Call's managing editor, responsible for its campaign and elections coverage. Before joining Roll Call in 2015, John helped direct CNN Digital's political and government coverage and the 2008 and 2012 presidential elections. Before that he served as homepage, U.S., and features editor. Before joining CNN, John was a reporter, artist, designer and editor at newspapers in Florida, Georgia, North Carolina and New York. John is a native of Washington state and is likely to never get over the loss of the Sonics. Or Super Bowl XLIX.

Kelly Mejdrich joined CQ Roll Call as policy reporter in January 2015. Before that, she covered transportation at the Orange County Register. Mejdrich started her career in public affairs reporting in her home state of Arizona, where she also worked as a journalism fellow at the Arizona State Legislature.

Warren Rojas is a general assignment reporter and features writer at Roll Call. He started at the publication as a Heard on the Hill columnist and later contributed to weekly dining coverage. Rojas reviewed restaurants as founding dining editor at Northern Virginia Magazine and helped carve out an investigative reporter post at Tax Notes Magazine.

Alex Gangitano is the Heard on the Hill reporter for Roll Call. She previously was on the CQNow team and was a staff writer for CQ and CQ Weekly. Alex’s other journalism experience includes internships at the New Yorker and National Journal. A native of the D.C. area, she graduated from Villanova University in 2014 with degrees in political science and English.

Lerman is editor of Budget Tracker, the daily compendium of all issues related to federal spending and the budget. He previously served as a national security reporter for Bloomberg News, where he covered defense spending and foreign policy matters. A native of Newton, Mass., Lerman is a graduate of Brown University, where he majored in political science and international relations. He now resides in the Logan Circle neighborhood of Washington, D.C.

Stacey Goers works in the Members and Information department at CQ Roll Call. She writes profiles of members of Congress for CQ.com, Roll Call and Politics in America, while maintaining the biographical information on the lawmakers. She also works with the data on and descriptions of congressional districts, looking at everything from census data to political breakdowns to geographical descriptions. Stacey also keeps information on committee staff and caucuses for CQ Roll Call. She joined Congressional Quarterly in September 2008, first tracking down various congressional documents and then watching House and Senate floor action. An Illinois native, she's a 2008 graduate of Miami University of Ohio, where she was editor of The Miami Student newspaper.

Leslie Sanchez is a political analyst and public opinion researcher specializing in Hispanic-Latino engagement and the women's sector. Previously she served as executive director of the White House Initiative on Hispanic Education under President George W. Bush. She's the author of You've Come a Long Way, Maybe and Los Republicanos: Why Hispanics and Republicans Need Each Other.

Rebecca Gale is an award-winning journalist at Roll Call who has covered wide-ranging issues, from landing a job on Capitol Hill, student loan reimbursements, maternity and paternity leave, and childcare for working parents. Her story on pumping options for Capitol Hill mothers, The Other Back Room: Breastfeeding on Capitol Hill, won a business reporting award from the MDDC Press Association. Her short stories have appeared in anthologies published by Boxfire Press, and her debut novel, "Trying," was published by Boxfire Press in December 2012. Prior to coming to CQ Roll Call, Rebecca worked as a press secretary and communications director for senators and members of Congress on Capitol Hill. She has also worked on presidential and congressional campaigns, both as spokesperson and communications director. She graduated with honors from Miami University in Ohio and has a master's degree in political communication from the Johns Hopkins University.

Eli Yokley is a political reporter at Roll Call. Yokley began his career covering Missouri and national politics in the spring of 2010 while he was 18-years-old and graduating high school. There, he covered the contentious House primary race in Southwest Missouri that was created by Roy Blunt's decision to run successfully for U.S. Senate, coverage that propelled Yokley to national recognition for his shoe-leather journalism on PoliticMo.com. Yokley is from Webb City, Mo., and graduated from the University of Missouri-Columbia in 2015.

Kate Ackley covers lobbying, influence and political money for CQ. She is an expert on K Street and the relationship between Congress and those seeking to influence it. She previously covered financial services, banking, housing and trade policy for CQ as well as lobbying for Roll Call and Legal Times/Influence. She covered state, local and national politics and government issues during internships with The Wall Street Journal, Reader's Digest magazine and the Fort Collins Coloradoan. Ackley grew up in Denver and graduated from the University of Colorado.
Matt Lewis is a Senior Contributor at the Daily Caller and author of Too Dumb to Fail: How the GOP Won Elections by Sacrificing Its Ideas (And How It Can Reclaim Its Conservative Roots).

Charlene Carter covers House floor activity as a staff writer at CQ Roll Call. Prior to taking over a House beat in 2012, Charlene covered banking and financial services issues for CQ Roll Call. She began covering Congress nearly a decade ago as a CQ.com intern and has covered the Capitol for either CQ or Roll Call's CongressNow for the past eight years. A Georgia native, Charlene graduated from Howard University with a journalism degree and currently lives in Maryland.

Senior Editor David Hawkings writes the "Hawkings Here" blog and column for Roll Call. His aim is to provide penetrating, non-partisan and forward-looking analysis of policies being formed on Capitol Hill and the people and politics driving the debates. Hawkings has been a passionate Congress-watcher at CQ Roll Call for two decades. Before his current assignment, he spent two years as founding editor of the company's Daily Briefing and six years as managing editor of CQ Weekly. He's also been senior editor for legislative affairs; the magazine's economics editor and its congressional affairs editor; and co-editor of "Politics in America", the signature reference work on members of Congress. He offers analysis every Monday and Friday on NPR's Washington affiliats, WAMU, and is a regular guest analyst on Fox News, CNN and MSNBC. Before joining the company, he was a correspondent in the Washington Bureau of Thomson Newspapers and a reporter, columnist and editor at the San Antonio Light. He's a native of New York and a graduate of Bucknell University.

Charlie Mitchell is a former editor of Roll Call who writes a weekly "Potomac Watch" column for several newspapers in Iowa. Charlie is also a senior editor at Inside Washington Publishers and a former managing editor of National Journal's CongressDaily.

Karin Fuog covers small business, finance, agriculture, education, technology and consumer protection, as well as other areas, by writing summaries and analyses of bills as they are brought to the House floor. Before joining House Action Reports, she worked as a policy analyst for a student loan servicing company. Born in New Jersey and raised in western Canada, Karin has lived and worked across the United States: Michigan while earning her doctorate in medieval English literature, Connecticut teaching college English and coordinating projects for the shipyard Mystic Seaport, Nebraska analyzing education policy, and now in Maryland.

George LeVines is Roll Call’s assistant managing editor. He’s helping the team strengthen its digital core and transition to a dynamic, web-first culture. Previously, he wrestled with government records at MuckRock and wrangled content as Defense One’s digital editor. He hails from outside Boston but currently lives in the District.

Alex Roarty joined CQ Roll Call as a senior political reporter in February of 2015, after working for five years at National Journal. Roarty has covered politics since graduating in 2007 from Lehigh University, first in Pennsylvania and later in Washington. He lives in the District of Columbia.

Rema Rahman writes about security issues at the Capitol as well as day to day life on the Hill. She has covered local, state and national politics and policy for The Annapolis Capital and The Associated Press. She is a graduate of Northwestern University’s Medill School of Journalism.

Phyllis Jordan edits congressional news for Roll Call, leading a team of reporters covering the day-to-day politics of Capitol Hill, as well as security and ethics issues. Before coming to Roll Call, Jordan worked as an editor for The Washington Post and Los Angeles Times. As a reporter, she covered Congress and the Pentagon for The Virginian-Pilot in Norfolk, home to the largest Navy base in the world. Jordan grew up in Lexington, Va., and graduated from Sweet Briar College and the University of Missouri-Columbia.

Stephanie Akin covers house leadership for Roll Call with an eye toward profiles analysis and news features. She previously was a general assignment reporter for The Record in Bergen County, New Jersey, where she covered major stories in New York City, New Jersey, Massachusetts, including the Sandy Hook school shootings, the George Washington Bridge lane closure investigation and the political corruption trials stemming from the "operation bid rig" bribery and money laundering sting. She has lived and worked in Germany, France and Senegal. She has Masters Degrees in journalism and political reporting from Columbia University and is originally from a suburb of Kansas City, Missouri.

Thomas McKinless is a multimedia producer for Roll Call. He joined the team as a video editing intern in August of 2015 and became fulltime that December. He edits press conferences and Congressional floor video for the Roll Call website and is the lead producer for the David Hawkings’ Whiteboard video series. Thomas has had a lifelong enthusiasm for video production and filmmaking, and studied broadcast journalism at Virginia Commonwealth University.

Roll Call political editor Mary C. Curtis is an award-winning journalist and teacher. She was national correspondent for AOL's Politics Daily, a contributor to The Washington Post's She the People blog, and a Nieman Fellow at Harvard University. Previously, she has worked as an editor at The New York Times and executive features editor and a nationally syndicated columnist with the Charlotte Observer. She has also served as a senior facilitator with The OpEd Project at Yale University, the University of Iowa and the Ford Foundation.

Stuart Rothenberg is editor and publisher of the Rothenberg Political Report, a nonpartisan, nonideological political newsletter covering U.S. House, Senate and gubernatorial campaigns. He is also a twice-a-week columnist for Roll Call. His column covers campaigns, elections, presidential politics and current political developments. He is married, has two children and lives in Potomac, Md.

Walter Shapiro is a veteran of Politics Daily, USA Today, Time, Newsweek and the Washington Post. He is a lecturer in political science at Yale and a fellow at the Brennan Center (NYU). His book "Hustling Hitler: The Jewish Vaudevillian Who Fooled the Fuhrer" will be published in May.

Eric Garcia is a Politics Reporter for Roll Call. Previously, he covered politics and economics for National Journal and financial regulation for MarketWatch. His work has also appeared in the American Prospect and the New Republic. He is a graduate of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and lives in Washington, D.C.. He pretends to be good at guitar.

Award-winning journalist Annie Groer brings a distinctive voice to the worlds of politics, culture, design, lifestyle and 21st-century manners. She has been a staff writer for the Washington Post, senior Washington correspondent for the Orlando Sentinel and a presidential debate panelist. At PoliticsDaily.com, she created and wrote the Republic of Dish column in addition to covering campaigns. Her work has also appeared in The New York Times, TheAtlantic.com, as well as Town & Country, More and Washingtonian magazines. Since 1990, Annie Groer has been a member of the Gridiron Club, a pre - eminent group of Washington journalists.She has also chaired the judges’ panel for the Robert F.Kennedy Journalism Awards.She holds a bachelor’ s degree in Journalism with Political Science and English minors from the University of Maryland, and was a Russell Sage Graduate Fellow in Urban Studies at the University of Wisconsin. A co - founder of the Art Deco Society of Washington, Annie twice represented the District of Columbia in the National Chicken Cooking Contest and once danced across the Kennedy Center Stage with Liberace.She lives in Georgetown and is at work on a memoir.
Jeremy Lott is author of "The Warm Bucket Brigade," a history of the vice presidency.

Ryan Lucas started his career with The Associated Press in Warsaw in 2005, covering domestic and regional politics, fallout from the CIA secret prison program, and US plans for a missile defense base. In 2010, Lucas transferred to Cairo to work as an editor on the AP's Middle East desk. While in Cairo, he covered the Arab Spring uprisings and reported extensively from Libya during the war to oust Moammar Gadhafi. For the past two years, he was based in Beirut, where he covered the Syrian civil war, the rise of the Islamic State group and the broader turmoil across the region. He has reported from a dozen countries across the Middle East, Europe and Asia.

Adriel Bettelheim oversees coverage of health and tax policy for CQ News and has held senior editor and reporter positions with the CQ Roll Call for more than 12 years. He also has covered business and government for Bloomberg News, PolitiFact and the Denver Post and was part of the PolitiFact team awarded the 2009 Pulitzer Prize for National Reporting. He is the author of "Aging in America: A to Z," "Medicare Revolution: Profiting from Quality, Not Quantity," and has appeared as a commentator on CNN, Fox News, MSNBC, C-Span, BBC, NPR and local television and radio outlets.

Alisha Green covers technology and telecommunications policy, including issues such as cybersecurity, data privacy, Internet governance, patents and copyright, net neutrality, spectrum, and more. She has covered state government and politics in Michigan for The Associated Press and MIRS News. She previously worked at the nonprofit Sunlight Foundation analyzing state and local policies related to public records, open data and open meetings. She also led a nationwide research on campaign finance and lobbying disclosures. Green is a graduate of Michigan State University's School of Journalism.

John M. Donnelly is a senior writer for who specializes in defense and writes CQ's Executive Briefing-Defense, a blog on national security and defense issues. Prior to his arrival at CQ in 2004, he worked as a reporter (and later editor) at Defense Week, a newsletter that covered the Pentagon, the defense industry and the congressional defense panels. He has netted numerous awards for investigative reporting, and he is a frequent guest on television and radio news programs. He serves on the board of the National Press Club and is a member of the Standing Committee of Correspondents in Congress. He has a bachelor's degree from the College of William and Mary and he graduated from Gonzaga College High School in Washington.

Ryan McCrimmon joined CQ Roll Call in July 2015 after covering the Texas state legislature for The Texas Tribune in Austin. McCrimmon has covered political and international news for the Medill News Service, local and environmental news for Cville Weekly in his hometown of Charlottesville, Virginia, and Big Ten sports for the Northwestern News Network. He has also worked in the communications department for the Middle East Institute. McCrimmon studied journalism and Middle East studies at Northwestern University. He covers budget and appropriations for CQ.

arr.str: Chief Content Officer & Senior Vice President

doc.str: David Ellis is the Chief Content Officer for CQ Roll Call and has spent more than two decades covering business and politics in both the U.S. and Europe, and is skilled at deploying social media to reach the widest possible audience. Ellis is a former reporter at Time and People magazines and still enjoys reporting on a variety of national subjects. He lived in London for more than a decade, and was editor in chief of Moneywise, the U.K.'s leading personal finance magazine. In that role he served as a regular commentator on political and economic issues for the BBC and international media outlets. Ellis, who is a citizen of both the U.S. and U.K., lives in Washington with his wife and two sons.

Lindsey McPherson is Roll Call's House leadership reporter. She previously covered taxes for CQ and Tax Notes. A University of Maryland graduate, Lindsey got her start in journalism covering education and government and politics in Howard and Prince George’s Counties for the Baltimore Sun Media Group. Lindsey lives in the Atlas District neighborhood of DC and in her free time volunteers with with City Dogs Rescue helping place homeless animals in foster and adoptive homes.

Jonathan Allen, co-author of the New York Times-bestselling Clinton biography "HRC," has covered Congress, the White House and elections over the past 15 years. This is a homecoming for Jon, who won the Dirksen and Hume awards as a reporter for CQ – the first place he worked in Washington. A frequent political analyst on national television, he's also been Bloomberg's Washington bureau chief and Politico's White House bureau chief.
